<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>WRITTEN EVIDENCE TO PUBLIC ADMINISTRATION SELECT COMMITTEE: Call for evidence on charity chief executive pay</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">vidence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">from Institute of Fundraising [CEP0010]</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="font-weight:normal; line-height:15pt; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">About the Institute</span></h1><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 37.5pt; text-indent:-19.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Institute of Fundraising (registered charity in England and Wales (no.1079573) and Scotland (no. SC038971) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s the professional membership body for UK fundraising. Our mission is to support fundraisers, through leadership, representation, standards-sett</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing and education, and we champion and promote fundraising as a career choice.</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 37.5pt; text-indent:-19.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Institute of Fundraising is the largest individual representative body in the voluntary sector, with over 5,500 individual members and more than 350 Organisational members. </span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="font-weight:normal; line-height:15pt; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Evidence </span></h1><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Charities in the UK raised £</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">11.5 billion </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">individuals through </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">donations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">legacies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and fundraising activities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in 2010/11</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. This income is absolutely vital to charities, allowing them to deliver services and work to achieve their charitable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> objectives.</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The scope and breadth of the charity sector is huge. There are 163,000 registered charities in England and Wales, and of these the majority (over 120,000) have an annual income of less than £100,000.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This variation within the charitable secto</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r makes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">meaningful </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">comparisons between organisations of different sizes and causes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">impossible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and a ‘one size fits all’ approach to issues such as charity CEO pay should be avoided. </span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Charity CEO pay has generated press, political, and public interest since a series of articles beginning in August, starting with the Daily Telegraph article </span><a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/10224104/30-charity-chiefs-paid-more-than-100000.html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/10224104/30-charity-chiefs-paid-more-than-100000.html</span></a></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The question of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">what</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> level of pay is ‘justified’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is one</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">each and every charity trustee board </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to decide for themselves.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Charity trustees h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ave a clear duty: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Trustees have and must accept ultimate responsibility for directing the affairs of a charity, and ensuring that it is solvent, well-run, and delivering the charitable outcomes for the benefit of the public for which it has been set up.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Public perception of the remuneration levels of senior staff is something which all charities will have due re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gard to. However, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the most important factor for trustees in all the decisions they make has to remain </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">delivering </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the maximum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> impact on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">charitable objectives. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If the trustees’ experience leads them to decide that this can best be achieved through paying a higher salary to senior staff than all of the public would be happy with, then this is a decision which the trustees need to have the co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nfidence, legitimacy, and discretion to make.</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Government have committed to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">‘Respect and uphold the independence of Civil Society Organisations to deliver their mission’</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> When commenting on the pay of senior executives in charities, all MPs should respect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the right and ability of charity trustees to set pay levels that they deem appropriate, even if they do not agree with them personally. </span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In setting remuneration policies that are appropriate for their organisation, trustees do need to have the best infor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mation and guidance to hand. As such, the Institute of Fundraising welcomes the inquiry currently being convened by NCVO to establish the principles that should guide trustees as they set pay levels for senior executives.</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t is hoped that the Inquiry prov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ides useful guida</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nce for trustees in setting pay, and gives reassurance to the Charity Commission and Government that charities have appropriate remuneration policies which are set according to best practice guidelines. </span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1.9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, the introduction of new g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uidance, while welcome, will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have a limited effect on resolving</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a wider issue. There is a gap of knowledge and understanding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by the public on how charities work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, particularly the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">larger and more complex </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">charities,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">which needs to be addressed.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1.10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Part of th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e solution is for the charity sector as a whole to b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">etter and more consistent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ly communicate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> donors so that those giving money have a greater level of information on what their donation is being spent on and the impact that the charity is having in del</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ivering its mission. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Institute of Fundraising has guidance on ‘Accountability and Transparency’</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which aims to help charities explain how they work and what they achieve. </span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1.11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We also believe that future press stories or statements about senior pay within</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> charities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">should be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">more contextualised. As the ACEVO Pay Survey Shows for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2013 m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">edian CEO salary of £60k is small compared to many other comparable public sector salaries.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Furthermore, the figure of a salary on its own can never tell more than a small p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">art of the story. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Inclusion of elements of the breadth of a charity’s work, the numbers of staff it employs, the complexity of its work (for example coordinating disaster aid relief to foreign countries) the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">number </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of people that benefit,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">its impact, w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ould </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">all provide useful context for the public and aid a greater understanding of the work of charities.</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1.12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Thought should also be given to the potential consequences of negative ideas and connotations being established amongst the public when the media do n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ot provide this wider context. It is possible that some donors may have stopped giving money </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">since seeing the stories in the summer. Of course it is the donor’s right to give or not give as they chose, but we should be mindful of how media stories are rece</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ived and how donors may react to them; every pound that is lost through a donor cancelling a direct debit, or choosing not to give in the future, is money that will directly affect that charity’s ability to deliver services to their beneficiaries or work t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">owards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> achieving</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> their charitable objectives.  </span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">UK Civil Society Almanac 2013 </span><a href="http://data.ncvo.org.uk/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://data.ncvo.org.uk</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The Essential Trustee: What you need to know, Charity Commission </span><a href="http://www.charitycommission.gov.uk/media/94159/cc3_lowink.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.charity</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">commission.gov.uk/media/94159/cc3_lowink.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The Compact </span><a href="http://www.compactvoice.org.uk/sites/default/files/the_compact.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.compactvoice.org.uk/sites/default/files/the_compact.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.institute-of-fundraising.org.uk/guidance/code-of-fundraising-practice/guidance/accountability-and-transparency-guidance/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.institute-of-fundraising.org.uk/guidance/code-of-fundraising-practice/guidance/accountability-and-transparency-guidance/</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><a href="http://www.acevo.org.uk/leadingtheceoandchair?=&amp;nccsm=21&amp;__nccspID=1103&amp;erid=1672878&amp;trid=b9ad9dfc-dca9-4fff-bdf0-bff1e5466876"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.acevo.org.uk/leadingtheceoandchair?=&amp;nccsm=21&amp;__nccspID=1103&amp;erid=1672878&amp;trid=b9ad9dfc-dca9-4fff-bdf0-bff1e5466876</span></a></p></body></html>